00:54:51.655 --> 00:54:53.030 align:middle line:84%
What's going to
come out of that?

00:54:53.030 --> 00:54:54.571 align:middle line:84%
>>HOFFMAN: Well,
the perfect example,

00:54:54.571 --> 00:54:57.157 align:middle line:84%
again-- the reason
I'm so good at what

00:54:57.157 --> 00:54:59.490 align:middle line:84%
I do is because of all the
various backgrounds I've had.

00:54:59.490 --> 00:54:59.940 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yeah.

00:54:59.940 --> 00:55:02.439 align:middle line:84%
>>HOFFMAN: I was an oil analyst
on Wall Street for 10 years.

00:55:02.439 --> 00:55:05.130 align:middle line:84%
Not just a guy doing
bank stocks, I did oil.

00:55:05.130 --> 00:55:06.410 align:middle line:90%
I went on rigs.

00:55:06.410 --> 00:55:10.870 align:middle line:84%
I did all the studies of how
much it costs to produce oil.

00:55:10.870 --> 00:55:14.810 align:middle line:84%
And back then, oil was $20 a
barrel when I left in 2005.

00:55:14.810 --> 00:55:16.430 align:middle line:90%
Maybe it was $25 a barrel.

00:55:16.430 --> 00:55:19.910 align:middle line:84%
All the analysts were predicting
it would go down to $20 and $15

00:55:19.910 --> 00:55:20.760 align:middle line:90%
forever.

00:55:20.760 --> 00:55:23.660 align:middle line:84%
But the fact is the low
hanging fruit, as we call it

00:55:23.660 --> 00:55:27.990 align:middle line:84%
in the extraction
business, is quickly--

00:55:27.990 --> 00:55:29.490 align:middle line:90%
was quickly taken away.

00:55:29.490 --> 00:55:32.170 align:middle line:84%
The Gulf of Mexico, the
shallow stuff, is gone.

00:55:32.170 --> 00:55:33.550 align:middle line:90%
So they went deeper and deeper.

00:55:33.550 --> 00:55:34.616 align:middle line:90%
I was-- I did--

00:55:34.616 --> 00:55:36.240 align:middle line:84%
Deepwater rigs was
a big thing of mine.

00:55:36.240 --> 00:55:39.680 align:middle line:84%
I was on the Deepwater
Horizon, the rig that blew up.

00:55:39.680 --> 00:55:42.010 align:middle line:84%
And the fact is, it
blew up because it

00:55:42.010 --> 00:55:44.090 align:middle line:84%
was trying to do
things, to find oil

00:55:44.090 --> 00:55:46.210 align:middle line:84%
where they could
never find it before.

00:55:46.210 --> 00:55:49.140 align:middle line:84%
And they drilled into a place,
which is very high pressure.

00:55:49.140 --> 00:55:50.300 align:middle line:90%
And they didn't realize it.

00:55:50.300 --> 00:55:53.130 align:middle line:84%
It's so expensive to
drill oil that the Saudis

00:55:53.130 --> 00:55:55.550 align:middle line:90%
need $80 oil right now.

00:55:55.550 --> 00:55:57.390 align:middle line:90%
Saudis used to need $5 oil.

00:55:57.390 --> 00:56:02.600 align:middle line:84%
So the growth curve of
prices has been exponential.

00:56:02.600 --> 00:56:04.870 align:middle line:84%
And that goes for
any new technology

00:56:04.870 --> 00:56:06.670 align:middle line:90%
that people get excited about.

00:56:06.670 --> 00:56:08.790 align:middle line:84%
At one point it
was the tar sands,

00:56:08.790 --> 00:56:10.820 align:middle line:84%
much more expensive
than people thought.

00:56:10.820 --> 00:56:13.060 align:middle line:84%
And now the new
thing is fracking.

00:56:13.060 --> 00:56:14.470 align:middle line:90%
Oh, it's going to save America.

00:56:14.470 --> 00:56:15.100 align:middle line:90%
No, not really.

00:56:15.100 --> 00:56:16.850 align:middle line:84%
If it was really saving
America, and we've

00:56:16.850 --> 00:56:18.670 align:middle line:84%
had a huge increase
in production,

00:56:18.670 --> 00:56:20.890 align:middle line:84%
how come the price of
gasoline is at all-time highs?

00:56:20.890 --> 00:56:23.500 align:middle line:84%
And now they're finding out that
it costs a lot more to frack

00:56:23.500 --> 00:56:24.250 align:middle line:90%
than they thought.

00:56:24.250 --> 00:56:24.370 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yeah, exacly.

00:56:24.370 --> 00:56:26.390 align:middle line:84%
>>HOFFMAN: It causes more
environmental damage.

00:56:26.390 --> 00:56:28.350 align:middle line:84%
And by the way, it
depletes more quickly

00:56:28.350 --> 00:56:30.370 align:middle line:84%
than they thought, which
means more expensive.

00:56:30.370 --> 00:56:33.970 align:middle line:84%
So the fact is in the
oil business, where

00:56:33.970 --> 00:56:37.381 align:middle line:84%
you have a cartel supporting
prices, this is what happened.

00:56:37.381 --> 00:56:38.880 align:middle line:84%
And now in the gold
business, you've

00:56:38.880 --> 00:56:42.080 align:middle line:84%
had the cartel dramatically
attacking prices

00:56:42.080 --> 00:56:44.780 align:middle line:84%
for 15 years to the
point where, I mean,

00:56:44.780 --> 00:56:46.850 align:middle line:84%
all you have to do is
look at the numbers.

00:56:46.850 --> 00:56:50.670 align:middle line:84%
I mean, the mining industry
lost, I think, $40 billion

00:56:50.670 --> 00:56:51.790 align:middle line:90%
last year.

00:56:51.790 --> 00:56:55.230 align:middle line:84%
And this is a group with a
market cap of $3 billion.

00:56:55.230 --> 00:56:58.500 align:middle line:84%
They wrote off a quarter to
a third of all their assets.

00:56:58.500 --> 00:57:01.060 align:middle line:84%
And they've cut
their CAPEX in half.

00:57:01.060 --> 00:57:04.009 align:middle line:84%
Production of gold
peaked in 2002.

00:57:04.009 --> 00:57:04.550 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: OK.

00:57:04.550 --> 00:57:07.100 align:middle line:84%
So really quickly, because
we're about out of time--

00:57:07.100 --> 00:57:08.027 align:middle line:90%
>>HOFFMAN: Yes.

00:57:08.027 --> 00:57:09.360 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: --what does that mean?

00:57:09.360 --> 00:57:11.151 align:middle line:84%
Are we going to have
a more difficult time?

00:57:11.151 --> 00:57:14.150 align:middle line:84%
People who want to kind of flee
to silver, gold, and so forth,

00:57:14.150 --> 00:57:15.450 align:middle line:84%
copper or whatever, is it
going to be more difficult?

00:57:15.450 --> 00:57:17.910 align:middle line:84%
>>HOFFMAN: Right now, the paper
prices don't tell this story.

00:57:17.910 --> 00:57:18.270 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: OK.

00:57:18.270 --> 00:57:20.270 align:middle line:84%
>>HOFFMAN: They are
suppressed more than ever.

00:57:20.270 --> 00:57:23.190 align:middle line:84%
And the physical demand, as we
talked about India and China,

00:57:23.190 --> 00:57:26.550 align:middle line:84%
is at an all-time high
accelerating, not just

00:57:26.550 --> 00:57:28.925 align:middle line:84%
going up, accelerating rapidly
from all-time high levels.

00:57:28.925 --> 00:57:30.549 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Still a
good idea then if you

00:57:30.549 --> 00:57:32.480 align:middle line:84%
can get your hands on
any silver or gold?

00:57:32.480 --> 00:57:34.188 align:middle line:84%
>>HOFFMAN: What will
end the bull market,

00:57:34.188 --> 00:57:37.220 align:middle line:84%
as we say at Miles Franklin,
is the lack of supply.

00:57:37.220 --> 00:57:38.344 align:middle line:90%
If you don't have it--

00:57:38.344 --> 00:57:39.010 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Right.

00:57:39.010 --> 00:57:40.440 align:middle line:84%
>>HOFFMAN: --you're
never going to get it.

00:57:40.440 --> 00:57:40.981 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: OK.

00:57:40.981 --> 00:57:45.410 align:middle line:84%
So just a shining word
of good news anywhere?

00:57:45.410 --> 00:57:47.112 align:middle line:90%
We all have each other, right?

00:57:47.112 --> 00:57:49.570 align:middle line:84%
>>HOFFMAN: Well, the good news
is you can protect yourself.

00:57:49.570 --> 00:57:50.920 align:middle line:10%
>>REGINA: Yeah.

00:57:50.920 --> 00:57:52.620 align:middle line:10%
>>HOFFMAN: And not
just financially.

00:57:52.620 --> 00:57:54.990 align:middle line:10%
You can do so by
preparing for the worst

00:57:54.990 --> 00:57:56.040 align:middle line:10%
and hoping for the best.

00:57:56.040 --> 00:57:57.000 align:middle line:10%
>>REGINA: As always, yeah.

00:57:57.000 --> 00:57:58.810 align:middle line:10%
>>HOFFMAN: And in my world,
I'm in the financial world.

00:57:58.810 --> 00:58:00.309 align:middle line:10%
I don't talk about
the other things.

00:58:00.309 --> 00:58:03.180 align:middle line:84%
I say you still can
buy gold and silver now

00:58:03.180 --> 00:58:06.020 align:middle line:84%
below the cost of production
while it's still available

00:58:06.020 --> 00:58:08.216 align:middle line:84%
and protect your
family and your future.

00:58:08.216 --> 00:58:08.840 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yeah.

00:58:08.840 --> 00:58:11.465 align:middle line:84%
And I always say at this point,
and grow a garden or something.

00:58:11.465 --> 00:58:12.548 align:middle line:90%
>>HOFFMAN: Well, that too.

00:58:12.548 --> 00:58:13.810 align:middle line:90%
It's a good thing to do.

00:58:13.810 --> 00:58:14.020 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yes, indeed.

00:58:14.020 --> 00:58:14.920 align:middle line:90%
Thank you so much, Andy.

00:58:14.920 --> 00:58:16.900 align:middle line:84%
We'll check back in another
four to six months--

00:58:16.900 --> 00:58:17.620 align:middle line:90%
>>HOFFMAN: I look forward to it.

00:58:17.620 --> 00:58:19.369 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: --see how
thing are progressing.

00:58:19.369 --> 00:58:21.499 align:middle line:10%
That was a belly full
of economic news.

00:58:21.499 --> 00:58:23.540 align:middle line:10%
And it all comes down to
staying alert and taking

00:58:23.540 --> 00:58:25.010 align:middle line:10%
care of the basics.

00:58:25.010 --> 00:58:27.460 align:middle line:84%
This isn't meant to alarm
anyone, only to educate.

00:58:27.460 --> 00:58:31.610 align:middle line:84%
Until next time, thank you for
joining us here on Gaiam TV.

00:58:31.610 --> 00:58:49.334 align:middle line:90%